@Andrzej  

You have to cite a source. I know that seems absurd when your source is your own direct experience, but it's necessary, because, for obvious reasons, whatever change or addition you're making needs to be verifiable. "No personal research" is one of the cornerstones of Wikipedia.

I would also point out that having an edit reverted isn't necessarily the end of the story. You can go to the talk page and argue your point. If you can't come to an agreement, there's steps beyond that. It's a whole process, and I've been on both sides of it many times. It's not always fun, and you have to kind of leave your ego at the door, but it's doable.

@Oikofuge 

Anyone can correct Wikipedia.  But anyone can also disagree with your correction. If you're right, and you can cite a reputable source to support what you're saying, you can make it stick.

It's not some monolithic organization. It's volunteers, mostly reaching decisions by consensus. It's actually rare that an administrator has to step in.

@Bruce 
I found another way of correcting Wikipedia. I wrote a well-referenced blog post about an obvious piece of nonsense on one page, waited two years, and saw the page corrected, citing me as a reputable source.

